<paragraph blockId="168.[151,1436,1282,1670]" pageId="168" pageNumber="169">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1571,1597]" pageId="168" pageNumber="169">Remarks:</emphasis>
the western Atlantic 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sladen" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[568,824,1571,1597]" class="Asteroidea" family="Pedicellasteridae" genus="Hydrasterias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Forcipulatida" pageId="168" pageNumber="169" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ophidion">
<emphasis box="[568,824,1571,1597]" italics="true" pageId="168" pageNumber="169">Hydrasterias ophidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reported from the 
<collectingRegion box="[1099,1178,1571,1597]" country="Portugal" name="Acores" pageId="168" pageNumber="169">Azores</collectingRegion>
by A.H. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark" box="[1289,1436,1571,1597]" firstAuthor="Clark" pageId="168" pageNumber="169" pagination="371 - 377" refId="ref176404" refString="Clark, A. H. (1949) Echinoderms from the mid-Atlantic dredged by lhe Atlantis in the summer of 1948. Journal of the Washington Academy of Sciences, 39, 371 - 377." type="journal article" year="1949">Clark (1949)</bibRefCitation>
based on his identification of the material collected by 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Seamount (A. H. Clark" authorityYear="1949" box="[766,853,1607,1633]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Atlantis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="168" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[766,853,1607,1633]" italics="true" pageId="168" pageNumber="169">Atlantis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(sta 20: 
<geoCoordinate box="[950,1090,1606,1633]" degrees="37" direction="north" minutes="50" orientation="latitude" pageId="168" pageNumber="169" precision="15" seconds="30" value="37.841667">37°50’30”N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[1101,1244,1607,1633]" degrees="26" direction="west" minutes="00" orientation="longitude" pageId="168" pageNumber="169" precision="15" seconds="00" value="-26.0">26°00’00”W</geoCoordinate>
, 
<quantity box="[1256,1352,1606,1634]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.562" pageId="168" pageNumber="169" unit="m" value="2.562">2,562 m</quantity>
). Later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Dilman" box="[151,317,1643,1669]" firstAuthor="Dilman" pageId="168" pageNumber="169" pagination="25 - 42" refId="ref178863" refString="Dilman A. B. (2014) Deep-sea fauna of European seas: An annotated species check-list of benthic invertebrates living deeper than 2000 m in the seas bordering Europe. Asteroidea. Invertebrate Zoology, 11 (1), 25 - 42. https: // doi. org / 10.15298 / invertzool. 11.1.05" type="journal article" year="2014">Dilman (2014)</bibRefCitation>
attributed A.H. Clark’s records to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Perrier, in Milne-Edwards" baseAuthorityYear="1882" box="[704,856,1643,1669]" class="Asteroidea" family="Pedicellasteridae" genus="Hydrasterias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Forcipulatida" pageId="168" pageNumber="169" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="sexradiata">
<emphasis box="[704,856,1643,1669]" italics="true" pageId="168" pageNumber="169">H. sexradiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a known native to the Azorean deep waters.
</paragraph>
